tions and Suggested CDT Codes</h3> \r\n <h4>Abutment-Supported</h4> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor\'><p><br><strong>D6506 Prefabricated Abutment</strong>&nbsp; <ul><li>Most frequently for ceramic type restorations</li><li>Most frequently titanium, rarely ceramic</li><li>All should be \'engaging\' type</li></ul><div><br></div><strong>D6057 Custom Abutment</strong>&nbsp; <ul><li>Most frequently for cement type restorations<br></li><li>Can be made of cast gold alloy, titanium or zirconium</li><li>All should be \'engaging\' type</li></ul><div><br></div><strong>D6058 Abutment supported porcelain/ceramic crown</strong><ul><li>Tip 1: If made on a titanium abutment, use of a ceramic abutment with polycrystalline ceramic core (such as zirconium) for better esthetic outcome is recommended.</li><li>Tip 1: If made on a ceramic abutment, more transclucent particle-filled ceramics, i.e. e.max (Ivoclar Vivadent Inc., Amherst, NY) can be used without a significant risk of the abutment shade showing through.</li></ul><div><br></div><strong>D6059 Abutment supported porcelain fused to metal crown (high noble metal)</strong>&nbsp;<div><span style=\"font-size: 0.75em;\">Tip: Often used with a metal abutment (custom or pre-fabricated)</span></div><div><span style=\"font-size: 0.75em;\"><br></span></div><strong>D6061 Abutment supported porcelain fused to metal crown (noble metal)</strong>&nbsp;<div><span style=\"font-size: 11px;\">Tip: Often used with a metal abutment (custom or pre-fabricated)</span><br></div><div><div><br></div></div><strong>D6062 Abutment supported cast metal crown (high noble metal)</strong>&nbsp;<div><span style=\"font-size: 11px;\">Tip: Often used with a metal abutment (custom or pre-fabricated)</span><br></div><div><br></div><strong>D6064 Abutment supported cast metal crown (noble metal)</strong>&nbsp;<div><span style=\"font-size: 11px;\">Tip: Often used with a metal abutment (custom or pre-fabricated)</span><br></div><div><br></div></p></div> \r\n <h4>Implant-Supported</h4> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor\'><p><strong>D6065 implant supported ceramic crown</strong>&nbsp;<br> <ul><li>Secured directly onto implant</li><li>Screw-retained</li><li>Often involves a CAD/CAM engaging abutment, Zr or Alumina, is designed to support veneering porcelain</li></ul><div><br></div><strong>D6066 Implant supported porcelain fused to metal crown (titanium, titanium alloy, high noble metal)</strong>&nbsp;<ul><li style=\"margin-left: 22.78125px;\">Secured directly onto implant</li><li style=\"margin-left: 22.78125px;\">Screw-retained</li><li style=\"margin-left: 22.78125px;\">Porcelain veneered on either titanium and titanium alloy CAD engaging substructures or on gold alloy casted \'cast-to burnout abutments with machined metal engaging implant interfaces.</li></ul><div><br></div><strong>D6067 Implant supported metal crown (titanium, titanium alloy, high noble alloy)</strong>&nbsp;<div><ul><li style=\"margin-left: 22.78125px;\">Secured directly onto implant</li><li style=\"margin-left: 22.78125px;\">Screw-retained</li><li style=\"margin-left: 22.78125px;\">gold alloy casted \'cast-to burnout abutments with machined metal engaging implant interfaces.<br></li></ul></div></p></div> \r\n <h2>Procedures</h2> \r\n <h3 class=\'hasNoChildren\'>Impression</h3> \r\n <h3 class=\'hasChildren\'>Try-In</h3> \r\n <h4>Information</h4> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor\'><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Implant components are machined to fit very tightly. Usually a separate try-in appointment is not required.&nbsp; In situations where esthetics is priority, a single implant crown may need to be tried-in and sent back to the dental laboratory for improvements</span></p></p></div> \r\n <h4>Required materials and suggested implant components</h4> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor\'><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\">Manual implant screwdriver (short, medium or long depending on the clinical situation) <i>(figure 15 will be inserted here)</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s3\"></span><span class=\"s2\">Articulating paper</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\">Disclosing medium (i.e. fit checker) <i>(figure 16 will be inserted here)</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\">Burs, polishing disks <i>(figure 17 will be inserted here)</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s3\"></span><span class=\"s2\">Slow-, and high-speed handpieces</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s3\"></span><span class=\"s2\">Restorative/prosthodontics instrument cassette&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n\r\n</ul></p></div> \r\n <h4>Clinical Procedure</h4> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor\'><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Healing abutment or provisional implant crown is removed.&nbsp; For <b>cement-retained</b> restorations, the abutment is placed onto the implant first, using a <b>try-in</b> screw (<i>(figure 18 will be inserted here) </i>is used. It is important to note that try-in screws are not designed to be torqued. Often the dental laboratory is asked to fabricate a positioning jig, to help find the correct orientation of the abutment. Seating of the custom abutments can cause discomfort to the patient, as the emergence profile of the abutment may be significantly bigger than the healing abutment. In these cases, use of local anesthesia may be indicated. Once the abutment is seated, a periapical or bitewing radiograph may need to be obtained to verify seating <i>(fig 19 will be inserted here</i>). The crown is then tried in checking the proximal contacts first. Verification of marginal fit is followed by checking the occlusal contacts.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Screw-retained single implant crowns are tried in a similar way. Since the crown is made directly on the abutment, it is carried into the mouth, abutment screw is tightened slowly and proximal contacts are checked first. (fig 20 will be inserted here) If the clinician believes that proximal contacts are acceptable, then a periapical or bitewing radiograph is obtained. Occlusion is checked last.</span></p></p></div> \r\n <h4>Sample Case Notes</h4> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor\'><p>TBA</p></div> \r\n <h4>Postoperative Instructions</h4> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor\'><p>TBA</p></div> \r\n <h3 class=\'hasChildren\'>Insertion</h3> \r\n <h4>Required materials and suggested implant components</h4> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor\'><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\">Manual implant screwdriver (short, medium or long depending on the clinical situation) <i>(figure 15 will be inserted here)</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\"><i>Manual torque wrench</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\"><i>Machine heads for torque wrench</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s3\"></span><span class=\"s2\">Articulating paper</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\">Disclosing medium (i.e. fit checker) <i>(figure 16 will be inserted here)</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\"><i>Gutta-percha</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\"><i>Composite resin</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\"><i>Cotton-pellets</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\">Burs, polishing disks <i>(figure 17 will be inserted here)</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s3\"></span><span class=\"s2\">Slow-, and high-speed handpieces</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s3\"></span><span class=\"s2\">Restorative/prosthodontics instrument cassette&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n\r\n</ul></p></div> \r\n <h4>Information</h4> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor\'><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">If the implant crown is tried in and found to be acceptable, then the abutment is placed using the appropriate final abutment screw. These screws are usually coated with dry lubricants and are designed to be torqued.</span></p></p></div> \r\n <h4>Clinical procedure</h4> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor\'><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">If the implant crown is tried in and found to be acceptable, then the abutment is placed using the appropriate final abutment screw. These screws are usually coated with dry lubricants and are designed to be torqued.</span></p></p></div> \r\n <h4>Sample Case Notes</h4> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor\'><p>To be added</p></div> \r\n <h4>Postoperative Instructions</h4> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor\'><p>To be added</p></div> \r\n <h2>Maintenance and Recare</h2> \r\n <h3 class=\'hasNoChildren\'>To be Added</h3> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor\'><p>tba</p></div></ul></div></div>','</div><div data-role=\"collapsible\" data-collapsed=\"false\" data-theme=\"a\" data-content-theme=\"d\"><h2>General Info</h2> <div data-role=\'collapsible-set\'> \r\n <div data-role=\"collapsible\" data-collapsed=\"true\"><h3>Material Options and Suggested CDT Codes</h3><ul data-role=\"listview\" data-inset=\"true\" data-theme=\"d\"> \r\n <li><a class=\'goToPage\'>Abutment-Supported</a></li> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor hidden\' data-page=\'page3\'><p><br><strong>D6506 Prefabricated Abutment</strong>&nbsp; <ul><li>Most frequently for ceramic type restorations</li><li>Most frequently titanium, rarely ceramic</li><li>All should be \'engaging\' type</li></ul><div><br></div><strong>D6057 Custom Abutment</strong>&nbsp; <ul><li>Most frequently for cement type restorations<br></li><li>Can be made of cast gold alloy, titanium or zirconium</li><li>All should be \'engaging\' type</li></ul><div><br></div><strong>D6058 Abutment supported porcelain/ceramic crown</strong><ul><li>Tip 1: If made on a titanium abutment, use of a ceramic abutment with polycrystalline ceramic core (such as zirconium) for better esthetic outcome is recommended.</li><li>Tip 1: If made on a ceramic abutment, more transclucent particle-filled ceramics, i.e. e.max (Ivoclar Vivadent Inc., Amherst, NY) can be used without a significant risk of the abutment shade showing through.</li></ul><div><br></div><strong>D6059 Abutment supported porcelain fused to metal crown (high noble metal)</strong>&nbsp;<div><span style=\"font-size: 0.75em;\">Tip: Often used with a metal abutment (custom or pre-fabricated)</span></div><div><span style=\"font-size: 0.75em;\"><br></span></div><strong>D6061 Abutment supported porcelain fused to metal crown (noble metal)</strong>&nbsp;<div><span style=\"font-size: 11px;\">Tip: Often used with a metal abutment (custom or pre-fabricated)</span><br></div><div><div><br></div></div><strong>D6062 Abutment supported cast metal crown (high noble metal)</strong>&nbsp;<div><span style=\"font-size: 11px;\">Tip: Often used with a metal abutment (custom or pre-fabricated)</span><br></div><div><br></div><strong>D6064 Abutment supported cast metal crown (noble metal)</strong>&nbsp;<div><span style=\"font-size: 11px;\">Tip: Often used with a metal abutment (custom or pre-fabricated)</span><br></div><div><br></div></p></div>\r\n \r\n <li class=\'last-li\'><a class=\'goToPage\'>Implant-Supported</a></li></ul></div> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor hidden\' data-page=\'page5\'><p><strong>D6065 implant supported ceramic crown</strong>&nbsp;<br> <ul><li>Secured directly onto implant</li><li>Screw-retained</li><li>Often involves a CAD/CAM engaging abutment, Zr or Alumina, is designed to support veneering porcelain</li></ul><div><br></div><strong>D6066 Implant supported porcelain fused to metal crown (titanium, titanium alloy, high noble metal)</strong>&nbsp;<ul><li style=\"margin-left: 22.78125px;\">Secured directly onto implant</li><li style=\"margin-left: 22.78125px;\">Screw-retained</li><li style=\"margin-left: 22.78125px;\">Porcelain veneered on either titanium and titanium alloy CAD engaging substructures or on gold alloy casted \'cast-to burnout abutments with machined metal engaging implant interfaces.</li></ul><div><br></div><strong>D6067 Implant supported metal crown (titanium, titanium alloy, high noble alloy)</strong>&nbsp;<div><ul><li style=\"margin-left: 22.78125px;\">Secured directly onto implant</li><li style=\"margin-left: 22.78125px;\">Screw-retained</li><li style=\"margin-left: 22.78125px;\">gold alloy casted \'cast-to burnout abutments with machined metal engaging implant interfaces.<br></li></ul></div></p></div>\r\n \r\n </div></div><div data-role=\"collapsible\" data-collapsed=\"false\" data-theme=\"a\" data-content-theme=\"d\"><h2>Procedures</h2> <div data-role=\'collapsible-set\'> \r\n  \r\n <div data-role=\"collapsible\" data-collapsed=\"true\"><h3>Try-In</h3><ul data-role=\"listview\" data-inset=\"true\" data-theme=\"d\"> \r\n <li><a class=\'goToPage\'>Information</a></li> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor hidden\' data-page=\'page10\'><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Implant components are machined to fit very tightly. Usually a separate try-in appointment is not required.&nbsp; In situations where esthetics is priority, a single implant crown may need to be tried-in and sent back to the dental laboratory for improvements</span></p></p></div>\r\n \r\n <li><a class=\'goToPage\'>Required materials and suggested implant components</a></li> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor hidden\' data-page=\'page12\'><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\">Manual implant screwdriver (short, medium or long depending on the clinical situation) <i>(figure 15 will be inserted here)</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s3\"></span><span class=\"s2\">Articulating paper</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\">Disclosing medium (i.e. fit checker) <i>(figure 16 will be inserted here)</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\">Burs, polishing disks <i>(figure 17 will be inserted here)</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s3\"></span><span class=\"s2\">Slow-, and high-speed handpieces</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s3\"></span><span class=\"s2\">Restorative/prosthodontics instrument cassette&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n\r\n</ul></p></div>\r\n \r\n <li><a class=\'goToPage\'>Clinical Procedure</a></li> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor hidden\' data-page=\'page14\'><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Healing abutment or provisional implant crown is removed.&nbsp; For <b>cement-retained</b> restorations, the abutment is placed onto the implant first, using a <b>try-in</b> screw (<i>(figure 18 will be inserted here) </i>is used. It is important to note that try-in screws are not designed to be torqued. Often the dental laboratory is asked to fabricate a positioning jig, to help find the correct orientation of the abutment. Seating of the custom abutments can cause discomfort to the patient, as the emergence profile of the abutment may be significantly bigger than the healing abutment. In these cases, use of local anesthesia may be indicated. Once the abutment is seated, a periapical or bitewing radiograph may need to be obtained to verify seating <i>(fig 19 will be inserted here</i>). The crown is then tried in checking the proximal contacts first. Verification of marginal fit is followed by checking the occlusal contacts.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Screw-retained single implant crowns are tried in a similar way. Since the crown is made directly on the abutment, it is carried into the mouth, abutment screw is tightened slowly and proximal contacts are checked first. (fig 20 will be inserted here) If the clinician believes that proximal contacts are acceptable, then a periapical or bitewing radiograph is obtained. Occlusion is checked last.</span></p></p></div>\r\n \r\n <li><a class=\'goToPage\'>Sample Case Notes</a></li> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor hidden\' data-page=\'page16\'><p>TBA</p></div>\r\n \r\n <li class=\'last-li\'><a class=\'goToPage\'>Postoperative Instructions</a></li></ul></div> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor hidden\' data-page=\'page18\'><p>TBA</p></div>\r\n \r\n <div data-role=\"collapsible\" data-collapsed=\"true\"><h3>Insertion</h3><ul data-role=\"listview\" data-inset=\"true\" data-theme=\"d\"> \r\n <li><a class=\'goToPage\'>Required materials and suggested implant components</a></li> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor hidden\' data-page=\'page21\'><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\">Manual implant screwdriver (short, medium or long depending on the clinical situation) <i>(figure 15 will be inserted here)</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\"><i>Manual torque wrench</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\"><i>Machine heads for torque wrench</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s3\"></span><span class=\"s2\">Articulating paper</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\">Disclosing medium (i.e. fit checker) <i>(figure 16 will be inserted here)</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\"><i>Gutta-percha</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\"><i>Composite resin</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\"><i>Cotton-pellets</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s1\"><i></i></span><span class=\"s2\">Burs, polishing disks <i>(figure 17 will be inserted here)</i></span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s3\"></span><span class=\"s2\">Slow-, and high-speed handpieces</span></li>\r\n<li class=\"li1\"><span class=\"s3\"></span><span class=\"s2\">Restorative/prosthodontics instrument cassette&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n\r\n</ul></p></div>\r\n \r\n <li><a class=\'goToPage\'>Information</a></li> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor hidden\' data-page=\'page23\'><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">If the implant crown is tried in and found to be acceptable, then the abutment is placed using the appropriate final abutment screw. These screws are usually coated with dry lubricants and are designed to be torqued.</span></p></p></div>\r\n \r\n <li><a class=\'goToPage\'>Clinical procedure</a></li> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor hidden\' data-page=\'page25\'><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">If the implant crown is tried in and found to be acceptable, then the abutment is placed using the appropriate final abutment screw. These screws are usually coated with dry lubricants and are designed to be torqued.</span></p></p></div>\r\n \r\n <li><a class=\'goToPage\'>Sample Case Notes</a></li> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor hidden\' data-page=\'page27\'><p>To be added</p></div>\r\n \r\n <li class=\'last-li\'><a class=\'goToPage\'>Postoperative Instructions</a></li></ul></div> \r\n <div class=\'relative descriptor hidden\' data-page=\'page29\'><p>To be added</p></div>\r\n \r\n </div></div><div data-role=\"collapsible\" data-collapsed=\"false\" data-theme=\"a\" data-content-theme=\"d\"><h2>Maintenance and Recare</h2> <div data-role=\'collapsible-set\'> \